{"title":"LUWA Dataset: Learning Lithic Use-Wear Analysis on Microscopic Images","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Archaeological lithic use-wear identification from microscopic images lacks a public, large-scale dataset. Ambiguous imaging magnifications and sensing modalities (texture vs. 3D surface heightmaps), along with complex wear formation, hinder robust model development and reproducible evaluation.","method":"The authors construct LUWA, the first open-source and largest LUWA dataset with 23,130 microscopic images, captured using an optical 3D profilometer at 20× and 50× magnifications and two complementary modalities (grayscale texture and 3D heightmap). Data span both machine-controlled and human wear processes to isolate material effects while reflecting real-world complexity, and include expert inputs (wear degrees, attention maps, and prompts). This design explicitly supports studying multi-scale wear patterns and modality effects while enabling reproducible benchmarking."},{"problem":"It is unclear how well state-of-the-art pre-trained vision models generalize to rarely seen microscopic wear-trace images, and which factors (image granularity, magnification, modality, training strategy) most affect performance relative to human experts.","method":"A systematic benchmark evaluates ResNets, ConvNeXts, ViT-H, and DINOv2 under varied training strategies (from-scratch, full fine-tuning, linear probing), image granularities (partitioning each 865×865 wear image into 6 or 24 patches with majority voting), magnifications (20×, 50×, or mixed), and modalities (texture vs. heightmap). Results show linear probing is most stable/optimal; higher magnification improves accuracy; mixing magnifications does not confuse models and helps; heightmaps often yield the best results while larger models tend to favor texture; and DINOv2 delivers the most stable performance. Models surpass human experts (≈49.5%); the best configuration achieves 67.05% top-1 (ResNet152, linear probe, heightmap, 24 partitions, mixed 20×+50×)."},{"problem":"Real deployments face scarce labeled microscopic images and newly discovered categories, necessitating effective few-shot classification and an assessment of whether large vision-language models can aid expert-like reasoning.","method":"The paper evaluates a simple pretrain + ProtoNet few-shot pipeline across multiple encoders (ResNet, ConvNeXt, ViT/DeiT, CLIP, DINO) over 600 tasks in 9-way-5/20-shot settings, analyzing magnification and modality impacts; and conducts GPT-4V case studies using archaeologist-crafted prompts for reasoning and few-shot classification. DINO-based encoders excel overall, with 50× texture consistently outperforming other settings in scarce-data regimes. GPT-4V can follow expert reasoning cues but performs poorly on few-shot classification, highlighting a gap between VLM reasoning and domain-specific visual discrimination."}]}
